title: Matchup: Stanford vs. Washington
text:
RECORDS: Washington 3-3/1-2 Pac-12. Stanford 5-1/4-0. 
KICKOFF: 7:30 p.m. at Stanford Stadium. 
TV/RADIO: ESPN/1050-AM. 
SERIES HISTORY: Washington leads 41-40-4, but Stanford has won eight of the past 10. 
STORYLINES: A win would further establish Stanford as the team to beat in the North and keep the 10th-ranked Cardinal in the College Football Playoff discussion. ... Collision of strength vs. strength: Stanford is averaging 48.5 points in its past four games while Washington leads the conference in scoring defense (16.8 ppg) and total defense (345.3 ypg). ... Stanford quarterback Kevin Hogan is 29-9 as a starter and leads the Pac-12 in passing efficiency (202.9) in league games. ... The Cardinal will face a freshman and/or backup quarterback for the fourth consecutive game. Washington's starter, true freshman Jake Browning, is questionable (shoulder). His backup is K.J. Carta-Samuels, a redshirt freshman from Bellarmine College Prep. ... Advertisement Stanford tailback Christian McCaffrey leads the country in all-purpose yards and rushed for 243 yards in his last game, a school record. ... There is no betting line on the game because of UW quarterback uncertainty. 
INJURY UPDATE: Stanford -- LB Noor Davis (leg), DT Harrison Phillips (knee) and LB Kevin Anderson (undisclosed) are out. Washington -- TE David Ajamu (knee) and CB Austin Joyner (knee) are out. QB Jake Browning (shoulder) is questionable. 
MATCHUP TO WATCH: Washington TB Myles Gaskin vs. the Stanford defense. ... With the irresistible object (Stanford's offense) facing the immovable force (Washington's defense), the other matchup could shape the outcome: Can Washington's struggling offense generate touchdowns against the Cardinal's inexperienced defense? It depends on the Huskies' running game. If effective, Stanford would be forced to guess. If not, the Cardinal could play for the pass. ... Gaskin rushed for 155 yards against Oregon and averages 6.3 yards per carry. 
STATS THAT MATTER: Stanford has rushed for more than 300 yards in three consecutive games, a school record. ... Washington is 11th in the conference in scoring, rushing and total offense. ... Stanford leads the league in third-down conversions (46.8 percent). ... Washington lists 52 freshmen and 24 sophomores on its roster -- and just 13 seniors. -- JON WILNER
